# Outline Standards

Use these standards whenever creating, reviewing, or optimizing PPT outlines.

## Core Principles

- **Visual carries the content:** The composition communicates each slide's narrative, sequence, contrast, or transformation before any text is read.
- **Text earns its place:** Bullets act as labels, anchors, and reasoning the visual cannot show; cut anything the visual already conveys.
- **One slide, one idea:** Resolve every slide to a single explicit takeaway, not a collection of loosely related facts.
- **Built for live presentation:** Design for an audience scanning in seconds while the speaker talks, not for a reader studying a document.

## Required Structure

```markdown
# PPT Outline: [Presentation Title]

---

## Slide 1: [Slide Title]
- **Label:** Self-contained explanation that states why the point matters
- Core insight: Main takeaway that ties the slide together
[Reference: path/to/image.jpg]
[Visual: Main composition and focal object; layout direction; recurring motifs; style constraints; no watermark or fake logos]
[Speech: Conversational presenter narration for this slide]

---

## Appendix: Global Visual Requirements
- **Theme:** Colors, accents
- **Fonts:** Title/body fonts and sizes
```

- Start with `# PPT Outline: [Title]`.
- Separate the title, every slide, and the appendix with `---`.
- Use sequential slide headers: `## Slide N: [Title]`.
- End every slide with one `[Visual: ...]` tag and one `[Speech: ...]` tag.
- Include one transition slide before each section — no transition before hook or call to action (see Slide Counting & Quotas).
- Include `## Appendix: Global Visual Requirements` after the final slide.

## Reference Image Tags

If a slide uses any specific reference images (e.g., a presenter's headshot, a specific diagram/chart reference, or a photo reference), you MUST explicitly declare them using a slide-scoped reference tag.

- **Format:** Use `[Reference: path/to/image.png]` or `[Refs: path/to/image.png]`. Multiple references can be separated by commas, e.g., `[Reference: path/1.png, path/2.jpg]`.
- **Placement:** Put the `[Reference: ...]` tag immediately before the `[Visual: ...]` tag of the slide.
- **Why it matters:** The image generation orchestrator only reads, loads, and sends reference images to the API if they are explicitly declared in a `[Reference: ...]` tag. Simply mentioning the image path inside the `[Visual: ...]` tag is NOT enough, as the orchestrator will not load it.
- **Supported formats:** `.png`, `.jpg`, `.jpeg`.
- **Path Resolution:** Relative paths are resolved relative to the outline file's parent directory or the workspace root. Always verify the file exists before referencing it.

## Slide Categories

Every slide is either a **content slide** (counted toward the requested slide count) or a **non-content slide** (NOT counted). The requested slide count always refers to content slides only.

### Content Slides (counted)

Teach one clear idea per slide with 5-6 substantial bullets and an explicit takeaway such as `Core insight:`, `Core logic:`, or `Anti-pattern:`. Content slides fall into three roles:

- **Hook (1-3 slides, at the beginning):** Grab attention and frame the stakes — the problem, tension, surprising fact, or question the deck will resolve. Required.
- **Sections (3-6 sections):** The body of the deck, where each section is a run of content slides teaching, demonstrating, or comparing one idea (concepts, workflows, case studies, conclusions). For a long section, optionally open it with a high-level explanation/overview slide that previews what the section covers.
- **Call to Action (1 slide, at the end):** The decisive next step, ask, or takeaway the audience should leave with. Optional.

### Non-content Slides (NOT counted)

Structural and navigational slides that frame the deck. Keep bullets minimal (2-4 lines):

- **Cover slide:** Opening title slide; make the premise immediately legible. Exactly one, at the start.
- **Transition slides:** One before each section (so 3-6 total, matching the section count); NO transition before the hook or call to action. Hook slides start immediately after the cover slide. Repeat the full roadmap or section map, bold only the current section, and include a visual progress marker such as `progress bar N/total`.
- **Ending slides:** Closing Q&A / thank-you slide(s) that visually reconnect to the cover. MUST include a clear take-home message — the single idea the audience should remember.

### Slide Counting & Quotas

- The requested slide count counts **content slides only** (hook + sections + optional call to action). Cover, transition, and ending slides are always extra.
- Every deck MUST divide its content into **3-6 sections**, with exactly **one transition slide before each section** (but none before hook or call to action) so the deck reads as 3-6 acts, never one undifferentiated run of content slides. The hook starts immediately after the cover slide.
- Make each transition slide detectable: prefix its title with `Roadmap:` (e.g. `## Slide 6: Roadmap: From Editor to Agent`) **and** include a progress marker such as `progress bar N/total` in its `[Visual:]` tag.
- Reuse one consistent roadmap/section-map composition across all transition slides, bolding or highlighting only the current section each time.

## Writing Standards

- Write self-contained bullets that make sense without relying on the slide title.
- Prefer `**Label:** explanation` bullets that explain why the point matters, not just what it is.
- Keep text supportive and compact so the slide is not forced to tell the whole content through bullets.
- Use summary bullets to make the takeaway explicit: `Core insight:`, `Core logic:`, or `Anti-pattern:`.
- Use tables for taxonomies or comparisons, and sub-bullets only for workflows such as `Plan -> Implement -> Test`.

```markdown
# Good
- **Clear Boundaries:** Each component should handle a single, focused responsibility
- Core insight: Systems perform best with clear interfaces and isolation

# Bad (too brief)
- Token limit: 128k-200k
- Performance: Fast
```

## Visual Tags

Write `[Visual:]` prompts as production-ready art direction that tells the slide's content faster than decoration or text alone.

- **Visual style ownership:** `[Visual:]` owns layout, composition, diagram language, icon treatment, recurring motifs, and animation intent. Do NOT restate these in the appendix — define them here per slide (or inherit from style reference images).
- Specify the focal object, foreground/background structure, and layout pattern: split-screen, grid, pipeline, roadmap, or system diagram.
- Show the narrative visually through contrast, sequence, hierarchy, cause/effect, before/after, or movement through a workflow.
- Preserve deck continuity with recurring motifs such as beams, nodes, panels, icons, section colors, or progress markers.
- **Two-tone backgrounds:** Content slides use the primary background color; non-content slides (cover, transitions, ending) use a slightly deeper/darker variant (~4–6 units darker in lightness) to create a visual "curtain" that distinguishes structural pauses from teaching slides.
- Keep generated-image text minimal; avoid dense labels, watermarks, fake logos, AI-generation stamps, and decorative text unless required.
- When reference slide images exist, extract concrete style rules from them and reuse those rules in later visual prompts.

## Speech Tags

Write `[Speech:]` as natural presenter narration.

- Expand on the bullets with context, emphasis, transitions, or examples not already visible on the slide.
- Aim for 60-90 seconds on content slides; use shorter scripts for cover, ending, and transition slides when appropriate.
- Keep the tone conversational, as if presenting live rather than reading a document.

## Appendix Requirements

The appendix defines **text-describable** deck-wide constraints only. Do NOT define layout, composition, diagram, icon, motif, or animation styles here — those are visual styles owned by each slide's `[Visual:]` tag and the style reference images.

- **Theme:** Color palette with hex codes (background, primary accent, secondary accent, warning/de-emphasis colors). Use two distinct background tones: a slightly brighter shade for content slides (readability) and a deeper shade for non-content slides — cover, transitions, and ending — creating a subtle "curtain" effect that signals structural pauses between sections.
- **Fonts:** Title, body, and code fonts with weights and point sizes
- **Format:** Optional numeric constants only (16:9 aspect ratio, safe-margin %, minimum contrast ratio)

Do not duplicate visual direction between the appendix and `[Visual:]` tags. If a style is easier to show than to write (layout, diagrams, icons, motifs), put it in `[Visual:]` only.
